---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout>
  <div class="page">
    <a href="/" class="back-link">← Back</a>

    <!-- ── Hero ── -->
    <section class="hero">
      <div class="hero-inner">
        <h1>Automatic Coal Feeder</h1>
        <p class="hero-sub">
          Stanford capstone project. Optimized design of an Automatic Coal Feeder (ACF) for scale manufacturing in Bangladesh.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-credits">
          Breno Casciello, William Sayler, Kilas Gallimore, Wooseok Kim
          &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Stanford ME&nbsp;170B Capstone, Winter 2026
          &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; In collaboration with BUET &amp; the Stanford Woods Institute
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Feature Photo ── -->
    <div class="feature-image">
      <img src="/acf-kilns.png" alt="Coal-fired brick kilns in Dhaka, Bangladesh ejecting particulate matter" />
    </div>

    <!-- ── Main Content ── -->
    <main>

      <!-- Overview -->
      <h2 class="section-label">Overview</h2>
      <h3 class="section-title">Automatic Coal Feeder</h3>

      <p>
        The ACF is a motor-driven coal feeder that dispenses fuel at a controlled, continuous
        rate into brick kiln portholes, replacing the irregular, hand-shoveled batches that cause
        incomplete combustion and particulate spikes. The Stanford and BUET collaboration has developed
        the concept over six years. Our AY26 charge was not to invent the machine but to make 100
        of them possible: redesign for manufacturability, cut cost by 35%, and reduce assembly time
        enough to build 10 units per week in Bangladesh.
      </p>

      <figure class="full-figure">
        <img src="/acf-assembled.jpeg" alt="Assembled ACF: 55-gallon drum on stand with motor, gearbox, and motor mount" />
      </figure>

      <!-- The Problem -->
      <h2 class="section-label" style="margin-top: 2.8rem;">The Problem</h2>

      <p>
        Bangladesh recorded the highest average particulate pollution in the world in 2023,
        roughly 16× the WHO guideline. The brick sector is the dominant source: ~23 billion bricks
        per year, thousands of fixed-chimney kilns, all fed by hand.
      </p>

      <p>
        The root mechanism is operator practice. Firemen shovel coal in batches every 15 to 20 minutes.
        Each large, irregular charge momentarily smothers the flame, drives combustion into
        oxygen-poor conditions, then cycles back to reignition, generating black carbon and CO with
        every feeding. A randomized controlled trial (Brooks et al., <em>Science</em> 2025) confirmed
        that more uniform fuel delivery reduces emissions by at least 43% without changing the kiln.
        The ACF operationalizes that finding.
      </p>

      <!-- How It Works -->
      <h2 class="section-label" style="margin-top: 2.8rem;">How It Works</h2>

      <p>
        A 55-gallon steel drum acts as the hopper. A motor drives a vertical shaft, rotating a
        central turntable sandwiched between two fixed plates. The turntable's eight pockets capture
        coal from the top plate's four inlet holes, carry it 45° around, then drop it through the
        bottom plate's four outlet holes, delivering eight discrete, metered charges per revolution
        across four kiln portholes. Plate speed sets feed rate; at 2&nbsp;RPM the mechanism delivers
        ~5&nbsp;g/s per outlet.
      </p>

      <figure class="full-figure">
        <img src="/acf-sandwich-diagram.png" alt="Exploded view of the sandwich mechanism" />
        <figcaption>
          Sandwich mechanism: top plate (1), turntable with eight pockets (2), bottom plate (3),
          aluminum+bronze inserts (4, 5) that define pocket volume and seal against coal dust,
          compression springs (6), and coal extractors (7).
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <!-- Design Challenge -->
      <h2 class="section-label" style="margin-top: 2.8rem;">Design Challenge</h2>

      <p>
        The previous prototype worked. It just couldn't be built 100 times. Four subsystems drove
        the cost and manufacturability problems: an oversized motor consuming more than 50% of total
        BOM, a motor mount requiring precise weld geometry on an inherently imprecise drum surface,
        a specialty sprocket that was expensive and over-specified, and all-brass inserts that used
        costly material throughout a part that only needed it at the sliding contact surface.
      </p>

      <figure class="full-figure">
        <img src="/acf-dfm-callout.png" alt="Exploded ACF diagram with callouts identifying the four DFM problem areas" />
        <figcaption>Four manufacturability bottlenecks targeted in AY26: motor, motor mount, sprocket, and inserts.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <!-- The Redesign -->
      <h2 class="section-label" style="margin-top: 2.8rem;">The Redesign</h2>

      <!-- 01 Inserts -->
      <div class="change-item">
        <div class="change-label">01 Sandwich Mechanism Inserts</div>
        <p>
          All-brass inserts replaced with a hybrid aluminum + bronze system. The aluminum body
          defines the pocket geometry and drafted 55° sidewalls that let coal fall free; a thin
          bronze ring sits only at the sliding contact surface where wear accumulates. This
          concentrates expensive material where it matters and makes the wear surface a planned
          replacement item rather than an uncontrolled failure mode. Archard's wear analysis
          projected 0.011″ of bronze loss over a full two-month season, well within the 0.15″
          available. Insert cost down 37%.
        </p>
        <div class="image-pair">
          <figure>
            <img src="/acf-turntable.jpeg" alt="Turntable plate with eight aluminum+bronze inserts and square drive at center" />
            <figcaption>Turntable: 8 aluminum+bronze inserts, square drive at center</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure>
            <img src="/acf-bottom-plate.jpeg" alt="Bottom plate with four outlet inserts, bronze wear rings visible" />
            <figcaption>Bottom plate: 4 outlet inserts, bronze wear rings visible</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 02 Drive Unit -->
      <div class="change-item">
        <div class="change-label">02 Motor &amp; Gearbox</div>
        <p>
          The previous motor consumed more than half the total BOM. The AY26 drive unit pairs a
          24&nbsp;V, 200&nbsp;W BLDC motor with an integrated 180:1 right-angle gearbox plus an
          additional 7:1 planetary reducer. Starting from 16.7&nbsp;rpm and 60&nbsp;N·m at the
          first stage, the combined unit delivers ~2.4&nbsp;rpm and ~407&nbsp;N·m at the
          shaft, a 180% margin above the 145&nbsp;N·m worst-case requirement measured in summer
          2025 testing. Drive unit cost down 52%.
        </p>
        <figure class="full-figure">
          <img src="/acf-motor-mounted.png" alt="24V BLDC motor with planetary gearbox mounted on the redesigned motor mount inside the drum" />
          <figcaption>StepperOnline 200&nbsp;W BLDC + Anaheim Automation 7:1 planetary, mounted on the adjustable threaded-rod mount.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>

      <!-- 03 Motor Mount -->
      <div class="change-item">
        <div class="change-label">03 Motor Mount</div>
        <p>
          The previous mount bolted to welded flanges on the drum exterior, requiring precise
          weld geometry and shimming to compensate for the drum's imprecise surface. The new
          mount uses threaded rods through oversize holes in the drum wall, clamped with oversize
          washers and nuts. Holes are drillable in minutes with a hand tool, no welding required.
          A slotted universal joint between the motor output shaft and the vertical drive shaft
          absorbs residual angular and z-axis misalignment. Precise alignment is no longer
          necessary; alignment by eye with a hand level is sufficient.
        </p>
        <figure class="full-figure">
          <img src="/acf-motor-mount-cad.png" alt="Redesigned motor mount CAD: oversize washers on threaded rods, clevis-pin universal joint" />
          <figcaption>Oversize washers clamp through holes in the drum wall. The clevis pin in an oversized shaft slot acts as a crude universal joint, absorbing misalignment without bearings.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>

      <!-- 04 Square Drive -->
      <div class="change-item">
        <div class="change-label">04 Square Drive</div>
        <p>
          The original sprocket was a precision purchased component with complex 3D geometry. Its
          replacement is a 7″ × 7″ square of ⅜″ mild steel plate, waterjet-cut from flat stock,
          press-fit and welded to the shaft. Stress analysis (FoS 4.72 analytical; 3.57 FEA) and
          Archard's wear analysis (3.63% volume loss per season) both confirm adequate margin. The
          part can be laser-cut locally in Bangladesh. Cost reduction: $85 per unit, 78% down.
          Corners trimmed to 45° to clear the aluminum inserts, a field fix discovered during
          assembly.
        </p>
        <figure class="full-figure">
          <img src="/acf-square-drive.png" alt="Square drive: CAD model and fabricated part assembled to turntable shaft" />
          <figcaption>CAD and fabricated part: 7″ × 7″ × ⅜″ steel plate. Waterjet-cut to match Bangladeshi laser-cutting shops.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>

      <!-- Testing -->
      <h2 class="section-label" style="margin-top: 2.8rem;">Testing</h2>

      <p>
        18&nbsp;kg of 15%-moisture coal was loaded and the motor commanded to 2&nbsp;RPM. Four
        weighed collection buckets were placed under the outlets; the run completed without
        stalling or clogging. The mechanism was disassembled immediately after for wear and
        dust-intrusion inspection.
      </p>

      <figure class="full-figure">
        <img src="/acf-teardown.jpeg" alt="Team tearing down the ACF after testing, coal-covered plates and buckets visible" />
        <figcaption>Post-test teardown, plates and inserts inspected for wear</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <!-- Results -->
      <div class="specs-block">
        <div class="specs-label">Results</div>
        <table class="specs-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="spec-key">Feed Rate</td>
              <td class="spec-val">5.55&nbsp;g/s mean across 4 outlets (5.03 to 5.86&nbsp;g/s range) · Requirement: 2 to 10&nbsp;g/s ✓</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="spec-key">Cost</td>
              <td class="spec-val">$1,646 BOM · 33% below previous prototype · Target was 35%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="spec-key">Assembly Time</td>
              <td class="spec-val">12 man-hours · Requirement: ≤16 man-hours ✓</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="spec-key">Drive Unit</td>
              <td class="spec-val">24&nbsp;V 200&nbsp;W BLDC · 180:1 + 7:1 planetary · ~407&nbsp;N·m output · 180% torque margin</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="spec-key">Operating Speed</td>
              <td class="spec-val">2.0 to 2.4&nbsp;RPM at shaft</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="spec-key">Coal Condition</td>
              <td class="spec-val">15% moisture (field condition)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="spec-key">Bronze Wear (calc.)</td>
              <td class="spec-val">0.011″ over 2-month season · Limit: 0.15″</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="spec-key">Deployment Target</td>
              <td class="spec-val">100 units · October 2026 kiln season · Bangladesh</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- Team Photo -->
      <figure class="full-figure" style="margin-top: 3rem;">
        <img src="/acf-team.png" alt="Team with assembled ACF: coach Steve Horne, Breno Casciello, William Sayler, Kilas Gallimore, Wooseok Kim, and CA Catalina Melentyev" />
        <figcaption>With coach Steve Horne (far left) after bench testing. Team left to right: Horne, Casciello, Sayler, Gallimore, Kim, Melentyev.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <div class="bottom-credits">
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.25740/rg783dp0539" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="doi-link">Stanford Digital Repository</a>
      </div>

    </main>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  * { box-sizing: border-box; }

  .page {
    font-family: 'Inter', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif;
    -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
  }

  .back-link {
    position: fixed;
    top: 2rem;
    left: 2.5rem;
    z-index: 100;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: #aaa;
    text-decoration: none;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    transition: color 0.15s ease;
  }
  .back-link:hover { color: #333; }

  /* ── Hero ── */
  .hero {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    padding: 7rem 2.5rem 5rem;
    background: #fff;
  }

  .hero-inner { max-width: 660px; }

  .hero h1 {
    font-size: 3.8rem;
    font-weight: 300;
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
    color: #0a0a0a;
    margin: 0 0 1.4rem;
    line-height: 1.05;
  }

  .hero-sub {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: #555;
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0 0 1.8rem;
    max-width: 540px;
  }

  .hero-credits {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: #aaa;
    line-height: 1.8;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
  }

  .bottom-credits {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    padding-bottom: 1rem;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: #aaa;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
  }

  /* ── Feature Image ── */
  .feature-image {
    width: 100%;
    height: 55vh;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: #1a1a1a;
  }

  .feature-image img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center center;
    display: block;
  }

  .doi-link {
    color: #aaa;
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-decoration-color: #ddd;
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
    transition: color 0.15s ease;
  }
  .doi-link:hover { color: #555; }

  /* ── Main Content ── */
  main {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 2;
    background: #fff;
    max-width: 660px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 5rem 2.5rem 6rem;
    overflow: visible;
  }

  .section-label {
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.13em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #aaa;
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
  }

  .section-title {
    font-size: 2.2rem;
    font-weight: 300;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
    color: #0a0a0a;
    margin: 0 0 2rem;
  }

  p {
    font-size: 0.925rem;
    color: #555;
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin: 0 0 1.4rem;
  }

  /* ── Full-bleed breakout ── */
  .bleed-figure {
    width: 100vw;
    position: relative;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    margin: 2.8rem 0;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .bleed-figure img {
    width: 100%;
    max-height: 55vh;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center 40%;
    display: block;
  }

  .bleed-figure figcaption {
    max-width: 660px;
    margin: 0.6rem auto 0;
    padding: 0 2.5rem;
  }

  /* ── Full-width Figure ── */
  .full-figure {
    margin: 2.5rem 0;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .full-figure img {
    width: 100%;
    display: block;
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: #f7f7f5;
  }

  figcaption {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: #bbb;
    letter-spacing: 0.03em;
    margin-top: 0.6rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  /* ── Image Pair ── */
  .image-pair {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .image-pair figure { margin: 0; padding: 0; }

  .image-pair img {
    width: 100%;
    display: block;
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: #f7f7f5;
    object-fit: cover;
    aspect-ratio: 4 / 5;
  }

  /* ── Change Items ── */
  .change-item {
    margin-top: 2.8rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #f0f0f0;
  }

  .change-label {
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.13em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #bbb;
    margin-bottom: 0.9rem;
  }

  /* ── Specs Table ── */
  .specs-block {
    margin: 3rem 0 2rem;
    padding-top: 2.5rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #ebebeb;
  }

  .specs-label {
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.13em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #aaa;
    margin-bottom: 1.2rem;
  }

  .specs-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
  }

  .specs-table tr { border-bottom: 1px solid #f0f0f0; }
  .specs-table tr:last-child { border-bottom: none; }

  .spec-key {
    padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem 0.75rem 0;
    color: #999;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    white-space: nowrap;
    vertical-align: top;
    width: 38%;
  }

  .spec-val {
    padding: 0.75rem 0;
    color: #333;
    line-height: 1.55;
    vertical-align: top;
  }

  .status {
    color: #aaa;
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #ebebeb;
  }
</style>
